t widely read of his writings today are, no doubt, his Confessions—the first significant autobiography in world literature—and The City of God. The preoccupations of those two works, like those of Augustine's less well-known writings, include self-examination, human motivation, dreams, skepticism, language, time, war, and history—topics that still fascinate and perplex us 1,600 years later.The Augustinian Tradition, like a number of recent single-authored books, expresses a new interest among contemporary philosophers in interpreting Augustine freshly for readers today. These articles, most of them written expressly for the book, present Augustine's ideas in a way that respects their historical context and the long history of their influence. Yet the authors, among whom are some of the best philosophers writing in English today, make clear the relevance of Augustine's ideas to present-day debates in philosophy, literary studies, and the history of ideas and religion. Students and scholars will find that these essays provide impressive evidence of the persisting vitality of Augustine's thought.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh  aancient greece.  aancient rome.  aaugustine of hippo.  aaugustine.  aautobiography.  achristianity.  achurch fathers.  aclassical learning.  aconfessions.  acontemporary philosophers.  adreams.  ahistory.  ahuman motivation.  ajust war theory.  alanguage.  aliterary studies.  aon christian doctrine.  aoriginal sin.  aphilosophical traditions series.  aphilosophy.  areligion.  areligious studies.  asaint augustine.  aself examination.  askepticism.  athe city of god.  atheology.  atime.  awar.  awestern christianity.  awestern philosophy.  aworld literature.1 aBittner, Rüdiger, econtributor.4ctb4ht